e,\n  "created_at": "2026-04-23T11:17:47.283215"\n}\n    \n        Create evaluation code that:\n        - Uses the correct fusion strategy\n        - Loads the fused output\n        - Loads the gold standard evaluation set (validation in sealed mode, otherwise test)\n        - Prints structured evaluation metrics\n        - Prints chosen evaluation functions in a compact one-line summary\n        - If helper modules are imported from local files (e.g., list_normalization), use a robust fallback import pattern that works from output/code execution context.\n        - Does NOT require exact matching everywhere by default.\n\n        EVALUATION ROBUSTNESS RULES (MANDATORY):\n- Use validation-set representation as the normalization target for evaluation.\n- Normalize fused and gold columns to the SAME representation before evaluating.\n- For country-like columns: DO NOT call normalize_country or any country normalization function.\n  The pipeline normalization node already ensures fused and gold values use the same country format.\n  Applying normalize_country in evaluation DESTROYS correct matches by converting to a different format.\n  Simply use tokenized_match for country columns, same as other text fields.\n- For free-text/list-like columns, avoid strict exact comparisons unless values are canonical identifiers.\n  Prefer tokenized_match with an explicit threshold (for example 0.7-0.9) instead of exact-only semantics.\n- If using set-based comparison on textual lists, first canonicalize list elements consistently across fused and gold.\n- Choose the right evaluation function per attribute type:\n  * tokenized_match: names, titles, labels, artists, text fields (handles word reordering like "The Beatles" vs "Beatles, The")\n  * year_only_match: dates and year columns (releaseYear, founded, publish_year) — keep values as STRINGS,\n    do NOT convert to pd.to_datetime() or pd.to_numeric() before evaluation. year_only_match extracts\n    the year component from string representations directly.\n  * set_equality_match: list-like columns (tracks, genres, categories)\n  * numeric_tolerance_match: durations, prices, ratings, scores (use reasonable tolerance —\n    for user ratings/scores use tolerance=1.0, for critic scores use tolerance=5.0,\n    for durations use tolerance appropriate to the unit)\n  * numeric_tolerance_match: also use for year/count columns stored as floats (e.g. publish_year, page_count) —\n    cast both fused and gold values to int before comparison to avoid 274.0 != 274 mismatches\n  * exact_match: IDs, codes, boolean fields\n- If the gold set does NOT contain a column (i.e. it is absent, all-null, or all-whitespace), do NOT evaluate that column.\n  Only evaluate columns that are present and contain meaningful non-empty values in BOTH the fused and gold datasets.\n  Before registering an evaluation function for a column, check: gold_df[col].dropna().str.strip().replace(\'\', pd.NA).dropna()\n  — if the result is empty, skip that column entirely.\n- IMPORTANT: For columns that appear to be nested sub-fields (they share a repeated prefix pattern like\n  "tracks_track_name", "tracks_track_duration", "tracks_track_position"), these are typically derived from\n  XML nested elements and are structurally difficult to evaluate accurately. If such columns consistently\n  show very low accuracy (<20%) in early evaluation attempts, DROP them from evaluation in subsequent\n  attempts — they waste investigation cycles on structural artifacts rather than genuine fusion errors.\n  Focus evaluation on top-level scalar attributes that directly correspond to gold set columns.\n- IMPORTANT: Before evaluation, coerce numeric-like columns (publish_year, page_count, year, count, rating, score)\n  to a consistent type in BOTH fused and gold DataFrames. Common pattern:\n    for col in numeric_cols:\n        df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors=\'coerce\')\n        if df[col].dropna().apply(lambda x: float(x).is_integer()).all():\n            df[col] = df[col].astype(\'Int64\')  # nullable int avoids 274.0 vs 274 mismatches\n  This prevents false mismatches from float vs int representation differences.\n- If the fused output contains an "eval_id" column, try fused_id_column="eval_id" first.\n  However, if eval_id coverage is low (many gold IDs not found), build your own mapping:\n  For each gold record ID, search the fused _fusion_sources column to find which fused row contains that ID.\n  Use ast.literal_eval() to parse _fusion_sources (it\'s a Python list as string).\n  This handles cases where clusters contain multiple records from the same source and\n  the pre-computed eval_id picked a different one than the gold set expects.\n        \n            Evaluation reasoning from prior pipeline run:\n            {\n  "action": "decide",\n  "diagnosis": "The dominant failure is incorrect entity clustering/matching, not fusion or normalization. The worst attributes (name, platform, developer, publisher, releaseYear) all show semantically wrong values from entirely different games, e.g. expected \'Plants vs Zombies: Garden Warfare 2\' fused as \'Lego Star Wars: The Force Awakens\' and expected \'NBA 2K12\' fused as \'Madden NFL 07\'. That pattern means the pipeline is combining records from wrong entities. Fusion choices cannot recover from wrong clusters, and normalization is not the main bottleneck because mismatches are mostly cross-entity value mismatches rather than systematic formatting differences. The cluster analysis strongly supports over-linking/ambiguous matches: very high one-to-many ratios (63%+), ambiguity ratio 73.3%, and recommendation for MaximumBipartiteMatching. Current matching F1 around 0.86-0.89 is not enough given downstream fusion sensitivity, and the current pipeline does not apply the recommended post-clustering strategy. Additionally, releaseYear/platform are being used in blocking/matching despite platform variants and year differences across editions, which likely creates/accepts near-name false positives within franchises.",\n  "next_node": "pipeline_adaption",\n  "reasoning": "Because blocking and pairwise matching outputs are already reasonably dense and non-empty, but downstream clusters are many-to-many and highly ambiguous, the most surgical next fix is in frozen-stage-allowed fusion/post-clustering logic: add the recommended MaximumBipartiteMatching post-clustering before fusion. This directly addresses the observed cross-game contamination while preserving the 14 attributes already above 85%. I am explicitly not recommending normalization first because the evidence is not format-driven overall; and not routing to run_matching_tester because the provided cluster analysis already identifies the actionable remedy within pipeline adaptation: post-clustering. Protected attributes such as ESRB and userScore are already at/near ceiling and should be preserved. Attribute-level resolver tweaks are low-value here because source-vs-validation exact rates are near zero for the worst attributes, showing structural limitations under current correspondences; changing fusers without fixing cluster purity risks regressions and will not solve wrong-entity fusion.",\n  "ceiling_assessment": "With current source coverage and attribute disagreement, the estimated overall ceiling is about 58.6%. Current 52.5% is only ~6.1 points below that ceiling. Applying MaximumBipartiteMatching should recover a meaningful portion of that remaining headroom by reducing false merges, but major gains beyond the high-50s are unlikely without deeper matching redesign or better source data alignment.",\n  "recommendations": [\n    {\n      "attribute": "post_clustering",\n      "issue": "No post-clustering is applied despite correspondence graphs being highly ambiguous and one-to-many; this causes fused records to contain multiple different games from the same source family, contaminating name/platform/developer/publisher/releaseYear simultaneously.",\n      "fix": "In pipeline_adaption, enable the recommended post-clustering strategy MaximumBipartiteMatching on the concatenated correspondences before DataFusionEngine.run. Keep existing resolvers for protected high-performing attributes unchanged.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "This is not an attribute resolver issue first; the evidence shows entity purity failure. All worst attributes fail together on the same rows with values from different games, which is the signature of bad cluster composition. MaximumBipartiteMatching is specifically recommended by the supplied cluster analysis for dbpedia-metacritic and should reduce many-to-one and one-to-many merges. Alternatives considered: StableMatching and HierarchicalClusterer. StableMatching is plausible but usually less globally optimal when many near-ties exist; HierarchicalClusterer risks retaining larger mixed clusters given the high ambiguity ratio. Fuser changes like voting/most_complete/prefer_higher_trust would still pick among wrong-game inputs and therefore underperform compared with fixing cluster structure first.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.04\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "name",\n      "issue": "Current voting resolver cannot correct wrong clusters; however name itself is structurally at ceiling under current correspondences, so do not change it yet until cluster purity improves.",\n      "fix": "Preserve current resolver during this iteration; reassess after MaximumBipartiteMatching. If cluster purity improves and name remains low, test shortest_string versus favour_sources/prefer_higher_trust using validation-aligned source comparison.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Source-vs-validation exact rates are only ~4% for all sources, indicating the current matched source values are usually for the wrong entity rather than a bad resolver choice. Changing to shortest_string now could even regress correct title variants on already-good records. Best action is to preserve and rev